g.text: Background
Parasitism is a ubiquitous feature of the natural world, with parasitic organisms present in every
ecosystem and found to exploit all free-living organisms [1, 2]. The life history of parasitic organisms
must be synchronised with the host to maximise a parasiteâ€™s individual growth, survival and
fecundity. However, the life history of external parasites (exoparasites) must not only be timed to their
host, but to variable and often stochastic external environmental conditions [3]. Such responses will
primarily be plastic when responding to local conditions or fluctuating environments, or genetic in
response to more predictable or spatially structured variation [4]. Understanding how genetic and
plastic differences contribute to life history trait variation in parasite species and populations is
essential for understanding parasite speciation, host-parasite interactions, and transmission dynamics
Parasitic plants are a group of c. 4500 species of at least 12 separate evolutionary origins that have
evolved a modified feeding organ, the haustorium, which allows them to attach to a host plant and
extract nutrients and water [6, 7]. Parasitic plants are incredibly morphologically diverse and present a
broad range of life history strategies [8], with the host species range a critical trait that determines
parasite interactions and performance in the wild. Generalist parasitic plants can attach to a broad
range of hosts with the grassland parasite
Rhinanthus
found to attach to over 50 co-occurring grass
and herbaceous species [9]. All generalist parasitic plants are exoparasites where the leaves, stems,
roots and flowers grow outside the host and only the haustorium invades and grows within the host
[10]. The range of hosts and their visible external growth make them ideal for investigating host-
parasite interactions. Generalist parasitic plants have been used in experimental studies for over 125
years [11], with these studies revealing that parasite growth, reproduction and metabolism are
determined by host functional group (herb, grass, legume etc.) and host species [12]. Despite this
large body of experimental work manipulating host type, most studies have not simultaneously used
